title: For Sale:  USMC 1903A1 SPRINGFIELD RIFLE (M1941) RARE! 1938 NRA Match Rifle
postcontent: Available for bid is a VERY RARE USMC M1903A1 (M1941) Sniper Rifle. This is a very nice example of a scarce early WWII USMC Model 1941 type sniper rifle as used by the USMC. These were some of the first, true purpose built sniper rifles used only by the USMC. This rifle was built on a 1938 Springfield M1903A1 NM rifle with a Lyman Bridge sight. The Springfield Armory receiver is serial numbered 1,526,xxx; this puts the rifle in the correct range of those used to complete the M1941 Sniper Rifle build. Originally, this rifle was built to compete in NRA Match Competitions. This rifle has the typical features associated with the USMC Sniper program rifles modified by the Ordnance Section of the Marine Corps Depot of Supplies in Philadelphia, PA. These features include: (1) Serial number in the correct range from 900,000 to 1,532,000. (2) Receiver exhibits the post 1936 second gas port as recommended by General Hatcher. Referred to as the "Hatcher Hole". (3) The receiver rails are polished in accordance with National Match specifications. (4) Unertl "O" and "E" scope blocks centered and mounted 7.2 inches center to center. (5) Rear handguard hand finished to afford correct clearance of front scope block. (6) Barrel is marked behind the front sight: "SA/Flaming Bomb/3-39" and stamped by Springfield Armory with the small star-gauge mark on the muzzle at the 6 o'clock position. Additionally, the barrel is coded "A 1242" under the front sight block. (7) Mounted with the later "D 1" marked bright polished Nickel Steel bolt, serial numbered to the rifle receiver (1,526,xxx). The Extractor is marked "CV" for Chrome Vanadium. (8) The rifle has an original pre-war walnut "C" stock with two reinforcing bolts, a single circled "P" proof in the pistol grip area along with the matching serial number and drawing number stamped on the rear underside of the stock. The stock has the correct heavy NRA Match checkered steel buttplate with trapdoor. Mid Band is an early milled type with milled trigger guard and floorplate. (9) This rifle had a NRA MN front sight blade with bead and comes with a P.J. O'Hare brass sight cover. The standard rear ladder sight is missing. (10) The rifle is mounted in a post-1936 "C" stock with SA/SPG cartouche. This firearm is a beautiful example of it's kind.
